# Testing

## Structure

- Follow **Arrange-Act-Assert** (AAA) pattern in every test.
- One logical assertion per test. Test one behavior, not one function.
- Name tests descriptively: `should [expected behavior] when [condition]`.
- Group tests by feature/module, not by function name.

## Test Pyramid

- **Unit tests** (70%): fast, isolated, test single units of logic.
- **Integration tests** (20%): test component interactions, database, APIs.
- **E2E tests** (10%): test critical user flows end-to-end.

## Best Practices

- Tests must be deterministic — no flaky tests. Mock time, randomness, external services.
- Keep tests independent — no shared mutable state between tests.
- Test edge cases: empty inputs, null/undefined, boundary values, error paths.
- Write tests before fixing bugs (regression tests).
- Treat test code with the same quality standards as production code.

## What to Test

- Business logic and domain rules.
- Input validation and error handling paths.
- State transitions and side effects.
- API contracts and response shapes.

## What NOT to Test

- Framework internals or third-party library behavior.
- Private implementation details — test public interfaces.
- Trivial getters/setters with no logic.

## Mocking

- Mock external dependencies (APIs, databases, file system), not internal logic.
- Prefer fakes and stubs over complex mocking frameworks when possible.
- Verify interactions only when the side effect IS the behavior being tested.
